...a fortune for his family
to last for all posterity.

494
00:41:45,200 --> 00:41:47,200
[BELL TOLLING]

495
00:41:56,300 --> 00:41:58,900
Death is not final.
It is merely the beginning.

496
00:41:59,800 --> 00:42:04,100
Gateway to an afterlife that reflects
our conduct here on earth.

497
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:08,100
God, in his infinite generosity,
has created heaven...

498
00:42:08,300 --> 00:42:09,800
...which is where Jason is now...

499
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:14,600
...surrounded by all the angels and saints,
looking down at us.

500
00:42:16,200 --> 00:42:21,100
And so we commit Jason's body to dust,
his soul already in God's care.

501
00:42:31,300 --> 00:42:33,500
Jason's ashes will be available
at the back...

502
00:42:33,600 --> 00:42:37,700
...but if you wouldn't mind, I'd like
you to leave through the front door.

503
00:42:41,300 --> 00:42:42,300
Morning.

504
00:42:44,200 --> 00:42:45,500
Please come in.

505
00:42:46,400 --> 00:42:47,600
Thank you.

506
00:42:53,200 --> 00:42:54,600
Morning.

507
00:43:58,600 --> 00:44:00,100
Good night, Jase.

508
00:44:01,800 --> 00:44:04,300
It won't be for long.
It's a short-term placement.

509
00:44:04,400 --> 00:44:06,100
Just until your mum feels better.

510
00:44:06,200 --> 00:44:10,400
The couple we have in mind have a lot of
experience and live close to where you live.

511
00:44:10,500 --> 00:44:13,200
Of course you'll stay at the same school.

512
00:44:24,600 --> 00:44:27,400
I don't wanna go with anyone else.

513
00:44:27,800 --> 00:44:29,500
I wanna stay with you.

514
00:44:30,100 --> 00:44:31,700
Where are you going?

515
00:44:33,400 --> 00:44:36,500
Just give us a minute, will you?

516
00:44:48,400 --> 00:44:53,000
Look, I need a little time
to sort myself out.

517
00:44:54,400 --> 00:44:58,300
But I'm not running away, I promise.

518
00:45:00,100 --> 00:45:04,900
I could stay with you now,
and I want that so much.

519
00:45:05,100 --> 00:45:09,100
But chances are I wouldn't make it,
because I'm not strong enough.

520
00:45:13,500 --> 00:45:15,500
[SOBBING]

521
00:45:18,400 --> 00:45:21,000
I don't expect you to understand.

522
00:45:24,500 --> 00:45:28,300
And I know for me to leave you now...

523
00:45:28,500 --> 00:45:31,700
...it must feel like the worst thing
in the world.

524
00:45:35,500 --> 00:45:39,000
But I promise you I'm not gonna
let you down, okay?

525
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:42,700
I promise you.

526
00:45:48,200 --> 00:45:50,000
I'm so sorry.

527
00:45:50,200 --> 00:45:52,200
I love you. Come here.

528
00:46:26,600 --> 00:46:28,100
Come here.

529
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:33,500
Be a good boy.

530
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:48,900
SOCIAL WORKER:
Come on.

531
00:47:05,600 --> 00:47:10,200
MARIE: Summing up France's postwar
history, only two statesmen counted:

532
00:47:10,300 --> 00:47:12,000
De Gaulle and him.

533
00:47:12,100 --> 00:47:17,000
On de Gaulle, everything's been written.
On Mitterrand, I want to finish the job.

534
00:47:17,200 --> 00:47:18,900
There are fascinating elements.

535
00:47:19,100 --> 00:47:21,300
The abolition of the death penalty,
the European Union.

536
00:47:21,500 --> 00:47:23,800
Coming from a right-wing family,
he seduced the left.

537
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:25,900
And what's more,
converted it to liberalism.

538
00:47:26,100 --> 00:47:28,500
Amazing! It was a revolution, right?

539
00:47:28,600 --> 00:47:32,600
Plus the darker sides of his character
that have never been explored.

540
00:47:32,800 --> 00:47:36,700
He's been dead for 10 years.
The timing is right, we can dig deeper.

541
00:47:36,800 --> 00:47:38,300
I want to dig into his past.

542
00:47:38,500 --> 00:47:41,400
Vichy, the Elf scandal...
What part did he play?

543
00:47:41,600 --> 00:47:43,500
The Taiwan frigates,
the Papon scandal...

544
00:47:43,700 --> 00:47:45,100
...Mazarine, Marguerite Duras.

545
00:47:45,300 --> 00:47:48,400
These stories were never really addressed.
They've all been buried.

546
00:47:48,600 --> 00:47:51,000
I'm going to tell who knew,
who didn't talk.

547
00:47:51,200 --> 00:47:53,900
[IN FRENCH] Isn't that going to bring us
too much controversy?

548
00:47:54,100 --> 00:47:55,700
[IN FRENCH]
I don't think so.

549
00:47:56,300 --> 00:47:58,500
What I want is a book
that can be read by all.

550
00:47:58,600 --> 00:48:01,400
Mitterrand was not just a politician.

551
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:04,000
Mitterrand was an icon.

552
00:48:04,200 --> 00:48:06,100
He's "Tonton," our uncle!

553
00:48:06,200 --> 00:48:08,500
Maybe that's what we should use
as the title!

554
00:48:08,600 --> 00:48:10,100
- Tonton.
- Heh, heh, heh.

555
00:48:15,700 --> 00:48:17,800
MICHEL:
I'm not sure we can keep that title.

556
00:48:20,700 --> 00:48:22,900
Of course not. It was a joke.

557
00:48:23,100 --> 00:48:25,600
I'll welcome your suggestions
for the title.

558
00:48:25,800 --> 00:48:30,700
How about Chipping Away at the Myth
or The Vacillating Statue?

559
00:48:31,600 --> 00:48:33,300
I look forward to your suggestions.

560
00:48:33,500 --> 00:48:34,500
We'll make a list.

561
00:48:34,700 --> 00:48:36,000
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

562
00:48:36,500 --> 00:48:37,900
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

563
00:48:43,400 --> 00:48:44,500
Congratulations.

564
00:48:45,700 --> 00:48:47,900
The timing couldn't be better.

565
00:48:48,300 --> 00:48:51,100
Politically, there's nothing going on
now anyway.

566
00:48:51,200 --> 00:48:54,500
You'll write the book you've always
wanted to. You'll get some rest.

567
00:48:55,600 --> 00:48:58,600
Come this summer,
you'll be back on the air...

568
00:48:58,800 --> 00:49:02,400
...with a bestseller under your belt,
and a big renegotiated contract.

569
00:49:03,800 --> 00:49:05,200
Stronger than ever.

570
00:49:05,400 --> 00:49:06,500
Exactly.

571
00:49:06,700 --> 00:49:09,100
Adapting and turning misfortune
to your advantage.

572
00:49:09,700 --> 00:49:13,300
That's what I've always loved about you,
never a victim.

573
00:49:13,400 --> 00:49:14,800
That's right.

574
00:49:14,900 --> 00:49:19,000
Never a victim, never vulnerable,
never complains.

575
00:49:19,800 --> 00:49:22,600
[IN FRENCH]
Excuse me. Your table is ready.

576
00:49:23,100 --> 00:49:25,500
DIDIER:
Great. I'm starving.

577
00:49:31,100 --> 00:49:32,700
MARIE:
Can I ask you something?

578
00:49:32,900 --> 00:49:35,800
What do you think happens
when we die?

579
00:49:35,900 --> 00:49:37,400
DIDIER:
That's a strange question!

580
00:49:37,600 --> 00:49:38,900
MARIE:
Tell me.

581
00:49:39,100 --> 00:49:41,900
DIDIER: When you die, you die.
The lights go out, that's it.

582
00:49:42,100 --> 00:49:43,500
Why?

583
00:49:44,700 --> 00:49:45,800
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

584
00:49:45,900 --> 00:49:48,500
That's it? Just blackout?

585
00:49:48,700 --> 00:49:51,800
Totally black, the plug's pulled out.

586
00:49:51,900 --> 00:49:53,300
The eternal void.

587
00:49:56,600 --> 00:49:59,100
Don't you think it's possible
that there is something?

588
00:49:59,300 --> 00:50:00,600
Like what?

589
00:50:00,800 --> 00:50:03,200
I don't know, something...

590
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:06,100
A hereafter.

591
00:50:07,500 --> 00:50:09,100
No, I don't.

592
00:50:09,300 --> 00:50:13,000
If that were the case, wouldn't someone
have discovered it by now?

593
00:50:13,200 --> 00:50:15,200
And there would be proof.

594
00:50:17,900 --> 00:50:19,200
I guess.

595
00:50:19,400 --> 00:50:20,700
[DIDIER CHUCKLES]

596
00:50:21,400 --> 00:50:23,500
Do you have a lot of questions like that?

597
00:50:25,200 --> 00:50:26,300
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

598
00:50:26,500 --> 00:50:27,800
More champagne?

599
00:50:28,000 --> 00:50:29,100
Huh?

600
00:50:29,200 --> 00:50:31,200
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

601
00:50:32,200 --> 00:50:33,500
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

602
00:50:47,700 --> 00:50:49,700
[SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE]

603
00:51:26,200 --> 00:51:29,000
CARLO: Okay, does everyone have
their blindfolds on?

604
00:51:29,900 --> 00:51:30,900
Okay.

605
00:51:31,100 --> 00:51:35,100
Now, if you wanna be a good cook,
first we need to work on your palate.

606
00:51:35,300 --> 00:51:38,800
To stimulate your imaginations,
your senses.

607
00:51:39,400 --> 00:51:43,200
No good being an expert chopper,
dicer, roaster, toaster...

608
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:48,200
...if you can't give names and colors,
and even shapes, to flavors.

609
00:51:49,200 --> 00:51:53,100
Okay. Now, spoon number one.

610
00:51:53,200 --> 00:51:57,500
Now, look, this isn't easy. So don't worry
if you don't immediately identify it.

611
00:51:59,400 --> 00:52:02,200
Let's start by trying to describe it.

612
00:52:03,100 --> 00:52:04,800
What is the texture?

613
00:52:04,900 --> 00:52:06,000
Okay, you ready?

614
00:52:06,200 --> 00:52:07,800
CARLO: What is the consistency?
- Open.

615
00:52:11,100 --> 00:52:12,400
Very good.

616
00:52:14,600 --> 00:52:15,600
[GIGGLING]

617
00:52:15,800 --> 00:52:17,100
What?

618
00:52:17,300 --> 00:52:19,700
I have no freaking idea what this is.

619
00:52:20,800 --> 00:52:23,300
GEORGE:
"No freaking idea." Okay.

620
00:52:23,500 --> 00:52:25,300
But, um...

621
00:52:26,500 --> 00:52:28,700
It's not a fruit.

622
00:52:29,500 --> 00:52:32,000
It's kind of nutty.

623
00:52:34,100 --> 00:52:39,600
- But it's kind of sweet too. I think.
- Okay.

624
00:52:39,800 --> 00:52:41,900
"A little nutty."

625
00:52:42,400 --> 00:52:43,800
"Kind of sweet."

626
00:52:44,900 --> 00:52:46,900
- Did she get it?
- Yeah.

627
00:52:48,100 --> 00:52:51,300
So how are we gonna do this?

628
00:52:51,500 --> 00:52:52,600
What?

629
00:52:52,800 --> 00:52:56,200
Well, we could make up a whole
load of crap, or we could...

630
00:52:56,300 --> 00:52:58,800
...cut to the chase and be honest
with one another.

631
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:00,300
About?

632
00:53:00,500 --> 00:53:04,100
About why we're both doing
night-school classes?

633
00:53:05,800 --> 00:53:07,300
CARLO: All right.
- Open.

634
00:53:07,500 --> 00:53:09,700
CARLO:
Everybody okay? How we doing?

635
00:53:15,200 --> 00:53:16,400
MELANIE:
Mm.

636
00:53:16,600 --> 00:53:18,100
There's, um...

637
00:53:18,300 --> 00:53:21,100
There's something oaky about that.

638
00:53:21,300 --> 00:53:22,300
GEORGE:
"Oaky." Okay.

639
00:53:22,500 --> 00:53:26,000
- Yeah. Nutmeggy? I think.
- Okay.

640
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:29,600
You're not gonna tell me it's
because you wanna make...

641
00:53:29,800 --> 00:53:32,400
...the perfect spaghetti vongole, right?

642
00:53:32,600 --> 00:53:34,700
No, not entirely.

643
00:53:36,500 --> 00:53:38,500
Okay. I'll jump in.

644
00:53:39,700 --> 00:53:45,600
I'm doing this because
I'm new to San Francisco.

645
00:53:45,800 --> 00:53:49,600
Because I'm looking
to make new friends.

646
00:53:49,700 --> 00:53:55,400
And who knows? If I'm lucky,
maybe even meet the man of my dreams.

647
00:53:56,700 --> 00:53:58,700
- Here, open.
- Okay.

648
00:53:58,800 --> 00:54:00,100
[WHOOSH]

649
00:54:11,800 --> 00:54:14,000
So why'd you move to San Francisco?

650
00:54:15,300 --> 00:54:16,900
Uh...

651
00:54:17,500 --> 00:54:21,400
Because I got dumped by someone
in Pittsburgh.

652
00:54:21,600 --> 00:54:23,200
Sorry.

653
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:28,200
Not quite at the aisle, but pretty close.

654
00:54:28,400 --> 00:54:33,600
Down payment on the wedding dress,
honeymoon booked. That kind of thing.

655
00:54:34,600 --> 00:54:37,700
I mean, it's okay. You know, I'm...

656
00:54:37,900 --> 00:54:41,400
I'm over it, just about.

657
00:54:43,100 --> 00:54:46,200
Not at all, actually.

658
00:54:46,900 --> 00:54:48,200
[CHUCKLES]

659
00:54:51,200 --> 00:54:53,000
What'd that taste like?

660
00:54:53,100 --> 00:54:54,400
Oh. Um...

661
00:54:54,600 --> 00:54:56,200
I don't know.

662
00:54:58,400 --> 00:55:02,200
I mean, I really... I don't...

663
00:55:02,300 --> 00:55:04,600
- Wanna try again?
- Yeah, okay.

664
00:55:04,800 --> 00:55:06,200
Okay.

665
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:10,700
- Ready?
- Uh-huh.

666
00:55:10,800 --> 00:55:12,300
Okay.

667
00:55:30,300 --> 00:55:31,800
- Is that a bean?
- Yeah.

668
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:33,800
- Really?
- Yeah.

669
00:55:35,500 --> 00:55:37,400
You know what color it is?

670
00:55:37,800 --> 00:55:39,100
It's like...

671
00:55:39,300 --> 00:55:42,000
Tastes like a black bean.

672
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:45,100
- Am I right?
- Yes.

673
00:55:47,100 --> 00:55:50,000
CARLO:
How we doing? Don't be shy.

674
00:55:52,900 --> 00:55:55,500
- Here we go.
GEORGE: Oh, well...

675
00:55:57,200 --> 00:56:02,500
...like you, I recently made
a big change to my life...

676
00:56:05,700 --> 00:56:10,500
...and I just wanted to reevaluate things
and change my priorities.

677
00:56:10,700 --> 00:56:14,100
What was...? What was the change?

678
00:56:14,300 --> 00:56:15,500
Divorce or?

679
00:56:15,700 --> 00:56:18,700
Oh, no, no, nothing like that. No.

680
00:56:18,900 --> 00:56:23,500
A job that I needed to put behind me.

681
00:56:24,900 --> 00:56:27,900
It was making
any kind of life impossible.

682
00:56:28,900 --> 00:56:30,100
Definitely a nut.

683
00:56:30,300 --> 00:56:32,300
[LAUGHS]

684
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:36,200
You're not gonna tell me,
you know, what the job was?

685
00:56:37,100 --> 00:56:38,800
Would you mind if I didn't?

686
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:43,400
I mean, don't worry,
I wasn't like a criminal or anything.

687
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:47,600
- Okay. So open up.
- Okay.

688
00:56:53,300 --> 00:56:54,900
CARLO:
No hitting on Alice.

689
00:56:55,100 --> 00:56:57,600
- Peppers.
- Yeah.

690
00:56:57,700 --> 00:56:59,800
MELANIE: Wasn't that great?
GEORGE: Yeah, fun.

691
00:56:59,900 --> 00:57:02,300
God, it's made me so hungry.

692
00:57:02,400 --> 00:57:04,500
Yeah, me too.

693
00:57:05,100 --> 00:57:06,900
Do you wanna get something to eat?

694
00:57:07,100 --> 00:57:10,200
Yeah. There's actually a place nearby
that everyone's talking about.

695
00:57:10,400 --> 00:57:14,900
Place nearby, are you kidding me?
We're practically experts ourselves.

696
00:57:15,100 --> 00:57:18,200
- I can drive.
- Yeah. Oh, yeah, great, okay.

697
00:57:39,100 --> 00:57:42,400
So you been in San Francisco long?

698
00:57:42,600 --> 00:57:44,100
Born and bred, yeah.

699
00:57:44,300 --> 00:57:45,900
Oh, nice.

700
00:57:46,100 --> 00:57:49,300
You can just leave all that. I'll get it.
You just get comfortable.

701
00:57:49,500 --> 00:57:53,400
No, I'm your partner. Remember?
I have to...

702
00:57:53,600 --> 00:57:56,300
- We have to do this together.
- Okay.

703
00:57:57,800 --> 00:58:01,400
Oh, my gosh. Are these?

704
00:58:02,300 --> 00:58:05,900
- This is you? As a kid?
- Yeah, that's me and my brother, Billy.

705
00:58:06,100 --> 00:58:07,300
[MELANIE LAUGHS]

706
00:58:07,500 --> 00:58:10,100
Let me tell you, you got the looks.

707
00:58:10,300 --> 00:58:11,700
Well, he got everything else.

708
00:58:11,800 --> 00:58:13,400
Are these his kids?

709
00:58:13,500 --> 00:58:15,400
Yeah. My nieces.

710
00:58:15,600 --> 00:58:17,200
Hm.

711
00:58:17,500 --> 00:58:18,600
Who's this?

712
00:58:18,700 --> 00:58:21,400
Is this some kind of ancestor?

713
00:58:23,500 --> 00:58:26,000
No, that's Charles Dickens.

714
00:58:26,200 --> 00:58:28,700
- Oh.
- I'm a fan. I'm a huge fan.

715
00:58:29,300 --> 00:58:32,300
You know, people go on and on
about Shakespeare and it's...

716
00:58:32,500 --> 00:58:35,000
I mean, he's great, of course,
but Dickens...

717
00:58:37,300 --> 00:58:38,900
No, no, I'll get that. I got it.

718
00:58:39,100 --> 00:58:41,900
There's a... There's a little trick.

719
00:58:42,100 --> 00:58:44,100
[PHONE RINGING]

720
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:47,900
BILLY [OVERANSWERING MACHINE]:
Hey. It's Billy.

721
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:50,200
Just to say I finally
caught up with our Greek friend.

722
00:58:50,300 --> 00:58:52,500
Told him to keep his mouth shut. Okay?

723
00:58:52,700 --> 00:58:55,100
Just relax. There shouldn't be
any more freaks...

724
00:58:55,300 --> 00:58:57,800
...knocking on your door asking
for readings, you know?

725
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:00,400
I gotta say though, this guy...

726
00:59:00,600 --> 00:59:03,400
...he made a big point of saying
how brilliant you were...

727
00:59:03,600 --> 00:59:06,700
...and with so many fakers out there,
someone who had a genuine gift.

728
00:59:06,900 --> 00:59:07,900
I don't know...

729
00:59:08,100 --> 00:59:09,100
[ANSWERING MACHINE BEEPS]

730
00:59:09,300 --> 00:59:10,400
GEORGE:
Sorry about that.

731
00:59:11,700 --> 00:59:12,800
Uh...

732
00:59:12,900 --> 00:59:15,800
- What gift?
- Oh, nothing. Don't worry about it.

733
00:59:15,900 --> 00:59:19,100
No, I mean, I'm interested.

734
00:59:21,200 --> 00:59:24,900
Well, the job I had before,
it was as a psychic.

735
00:59:26,300 --> 00:59:27,800
I know, but...

736
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:30,400
- What?
- But it's true.

737
00:59:31,900 --> 00:59:33,400
I had an illness as a child...

738
00:59:36,500 --> 00:59:39,700
...and I had an infection,
which turned into a fever...

739
00:59:39,900 --> 00:59:43,400
...which turned into inflammation
of my brain and spinal cord.

740
00:59:43,600 --> 00:59:45,500
It's called encephalomyelitis.

741
00:59:45,700 --> 00:59:50,200
And they had to operate,
in the back, here.

742
00:59:50,400 --> 00:59:56,200
It was a complicated procedure. It was
eight hours. And they nearly lost me.

743
00:59:56,300 --> 01:00:00,200
Actually, technically, they did lose me...

