992
01:21:01,800 --> 01:21:05,900
You know, the website's still up.
Waiting.

993
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:08,600
It'd be different this time, George.

994
01:21:09,500 --> 01:21:13,100
We could control it.
That's how it would be different.

995
01:21:13,300 --> 01:21:16,000
We'd only do two clients a day,
three, tops. Keep it small.

996
01:21:16,200 --> 01:21:19,000
Don't give out your phone number.
We won't talk to the media.

997
01:21:19,200 --> 01:21:21,700
We learned our lesson
with that the last time, right?

998
01:21:23,900 --> 01:21:26,400
Just think about it, all right?

999
01:21:34,000 --> 01:21:36,200
- Doing all right, George?
- Yeah.

1000
01:21:36,400 --> 01:21:38,300
Look a little bummed out.

1001
01:21:38,500 --> 01:21:40,600
Listen, I'll step in and partner with you.

1002
01:21:40,800 --> 01:21:43,700
Me and you could win this thing,
you know?

1003
01:21:43,900 --> 01:21:45,300
- Why not?
GEORGE: Yeah.

1004
01:21:46,000 --> 01:21:47,500
Great.

1005
01:21:47,700 --> 01:21:49,800
Watch your fingers there.

1006
01:22:10,900 --> 01:22:12,900
[RINGING]

1007
01:22:13,300 --> 01:22:15,400
- Hello?
DENNIS [OVER PHONE]: Clare?

1008
01:22:15,600 --> 01:22:18,100
Dennis. I think you should come over.

1009
01:22:19,200 --> 01:22:21,600
Yeah, of course, Dennis. I'll come now.

1010
01:22:24,200 --> 01:22:27,000
SOCIAL WORKER: How much was in here?
DENNIS: Two hundred pounds.

1011
01:22:27,200 --> 01:22:30,100
We called the school. He never got there.

1012
01:22:30,300 --> 01:22:32,100
What happens now?

1013
01:22:32,200 --> 01:22:34,500
Well, we don't want to
involve the police.

1014
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:36,600
No, that's really a last resort.

1015
01:22:38,600 --> 01:22:40,600
Will you let us know if he comes back?

1016
01:22:41,300 --> 01:22:43,100
SOCIAL WORKER:
We will be in touch.

1017
01:22:44,600 --> 01:22:46,600
I'll see you out.

1018
01:22:58,000 --> 01:22:59,500
MAN 1:
There you go.

1019
01:23:12,100 --> 01:23:15,100
MAN 2: I'm afraid our sensitive,
Mr. Hewitt, is very busy.

1020
01:23:15,300 --> 01:23:18,000
Earliest he could see you
is six weeks' time.

1021
01:23:18,100 --> 01:23:19,500
MAN 3:
Oh, dear.

1022
01:23:19,700 --> 01:23:21,700
Mrs. Joyce, our senior sensitive...

1023
01:23:21,800 --> 01:23:24,600
...is doing a public reading tonight
if you're interested.

1024
01:23:24,800 --> 01:23:26,500
In the lecture hall.

1025
01:23:26,900 --> 01:23:29,700
MAN 3:
All right. I'll try my luck. Thank you.

1026
01:23:31,200 --> 01:23:32,600
Can I help you?

1027
01:23:33,100 --> 01:23:34,500
Oh, no, thanks.

1028
01:23:37,500 --> 01:23:40,000
I'm getting a strong feeling
over this side of the room.

1029
01:23:41,600 --> 01:23:44,300
Someone whose name starts with a "J."

1030
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:49,800
Does the letter "J" mean anything
to anyone? Anyone?

1031
01:23:50,000 --> 01:23:51,700
Anyone?

1032
01:23:52,200 --> 01:23:53,400
Oh.

1033
01:23:53,900 --> 01:23:55,600
Don't be shy.

1034
01:23:56,500 --> 01:23:58,400
Tell us your name, please.

1035
01:23:59,400 --> 01:24:00,600
Marcus.

1036
01:24:01,300 --> 01:24:04,800
Marcus. Marcus. Come on.

1037
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:07,000
Come up here where I can see you.

1038
01:24:08,100 --> 01:24:09,500
Good boy.

1039
01:24:09,900 --> 01:24:14,500
There's a good boy, Marcus.
That's right. I'm not going to hurt you.

1040
01:24:15,800 --> 01:24:17,200
That's lovely.

1041
01:24:17,600 --> 01:24:21,700
Now, Marcus,
you've lost someone recently.

1042
01:24:22,700 --> 01:24:24,700
Was it someone very close to you?

1043
01:24:27,000 --> 01:24:30,400
He's telling me his name.
It's Joe, or Jack.

1044
01:24:31,100 --> 01:24:32,400
- Jason.
- Jason, that's it.

1045
01:24:32,600 --> 01:24:35,900
He was very close to you, wasn't he?
Was he part of your family?

1046
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:41,600
Is it your dad?

1047
01:24:43,900 --> 01:24:47,200
Well, Daddy says please don't be sad...

1048
01:24:47,400 --> 01:24:50,300
...and to look after Mummy
for him, will you?

1049
01:24:50,500 --> 01:24:52,500
Will you do that for him?

1050
01:24:53,300 --> 01:24:56,700
Give Marcus a round of applause,
ladies and gentlemen.

1051
01:24:59,100 --> 01:25:01,000
Lovely boy.

1052
01:25:01,200 --> 01:25:03,700
MAN:
And as I go into a trance...

1053
01:25:04,500 --> 01:25:08,300
...my spirit guide will speak to you
through me.

1054
01:25:09,300 --> 01:25:10,700
[SIGHS]

1055
01:25:11,800 --> 01:25:13,100
Oh.

1056
01:25:15,500 --> 01:25:18,400
[IN GRUFF VOICE]
Who summons me from the spirit world?

1057
01:25:19,800 --> 01:25:20,900
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Say your name.

1058
01:25:21,500 --> 01:25:23,700
- Marcus.
- Marcus.

1059
01:25:23,900 --> 01:25:29,100
[IN GRUFF VOICE]
Welcome, Marcus. My name is Yoshi.

1060
01:25:30,500 --> 01:25:33,800
What I'm doing is I'm adjusting
the level of the microphones.

1061
01:25:34,000 --> 01:25:35,600
Do you do physics at school?

1062
01:25:35,700 --> 01:25:38,900
Good. Then you know that all matter
vibrates at different speeds.

1063
01:25:39,000 --> 01:25:42,600
But in the spirit world,
operates at far higher levels.

1064
01:25:42,700 --> 01:25:45,300
So we can't hear them.
Not with our normal hearing.

1065
01:25:45,500 --> 01:25:48,600
So, what we really need
is an omnidirectional...

1066
01:25:48,700 --> 01:25:51,500
...supercardioid condenser microphone.

1067
01:25:52,000 --> 01:25:53,600
Like this beauty.

1068
01:25:53,900 --> 01:25:57,600
Right. I think we are ready.

1069
01:26:00,400 --> 01:26:01,900
And...

1070
01:26:06,300 --> 01:26:09,600
Jason? Are you there?

1071
01:26:11,200 --> 01:26:16,400
Your brother, Marcus, is here.
Is there a message for him?

1072
01:26:19,200 --> 01:26:22,400
It was the ancient Greeks
who first discovered it.

1073
01:26:23,700 --> 01:26:26,100
"Psychomanteum," they called it.

1074
01:26:26,300 --> 01:26:29,800
The reflective surface
being the conduit to the afterlife.

1075
01:26:30,000 --> 01:26:32,900
Nowadays, we call it "mirror gazing."

1076
01:26:33,000 --> 01:26:36,400
You might not be able to speak to him,
but you will see him...

1077
01:26:36,500 --> 01:26:38,700
...if you really want to, that is.

1078
01:26:40,700 --> 01:26:42,100
Did you see him?

1079
01:26:42,300 --> 01:26:43,600
No.

1080
01:26:45,500 --> 01:26:48,100
[PHONE RINGING]

1081
01:26:48,200 --> 01:26:50,100
Hello. Clare speaking.

1082
01:26:50,300 --> 01:26:52,600
There's no sign of him.
I'm gonna call the police.

1083
01:26:52,800 --> 01:26:55,600
CLARE: But that will not help.
- Well, I don't care what...

1084
01:26:56,300 --> 01:26:59,400
Hang on. He's here.
I'll call you right back.

1085
01:27:02,700 --> 01:27:04,300
I'm sorry.

1086
01:27:04,500 --> 01:27:05,800
DENNIS:
Ah...

1087
01:27:06,500 --> 01:27:08,100
Leave him be.

1088
01:28:16,700 --> 01:28:17,700
MAN:
Watch out!

1089
01:28:26,900 --> 01:28:28,300
WOMAN:
Excuse me.

1090
01:28:58,200 --> 01:29:00,200
[PEOPLE SCREAM]

1091
01:29:09,600 --> 01:29:11,600
[SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE]

1092
01:29:45,500 --> 01:29:47,300
SECRETARY [IN FRENCH]:
Sorry, we are running a little late.

1093
01:29:47,500 --> 01:29:48,600
Come in.

1094
01:29:48,800 --> 01:29:51,700
Everyone is upset by the events.

1095
01:29:56,100 --> 01:29:57,300
Sit down.

1096
01:30:00,500 --> 01:30:03,300
Marie, to be honest with you,
I'm a bit confused.

1097
01:30:04,300 --> 01:30:06,300
I thought we commissioned a book
about Francois Mitterrand.

1098
01:30:06,500 --> 01:30:09,100
Instead, you give us
the first three chapters of...

1099
01:30:09,300 --> 01:30:10,300
...Hereafter:

1100
01:30:11,900 --> 01:30:13,700
The Conspiracy of Silence.

1101
01:30:13,800 --> 01:30:17,400
[IN FRENCH] I realize it's not
what you were expecting.

1102
01:30:18,000 --> 01:30:20,900
You always said there weren't
enough surprises in publishing.

1103
01:30:21,100 --> 01:30:23,200
Well, this is certainly a surprise!

1104
01:30:28,900 --> 01:30:31,100
I don't know where to begin.

1105
01:30:31,300 --> 01:30:32,800
Did you at least find it interesting?

1106
01:30:32,900 --> 01:30:36,700
Of course.
You've always had a nose for a good story.

1107
01:30:36,900 --> 01:30:38,700
But we're a political publisher...

1108
01:30:38,900 --> 01:30:40,100
This is political!

1109
01:30:40,300 --> 01:30:44,500
This kind of material, however fascinating,
is for a specialized market.

1110
01:30:44,600 --> 01:30:47,700
JASMINE [ON TV]: This morning, in London,
six bombs went off in the heart of the city.

1111
01:30:47,900 --> 01:30:52,300
Apparently coordinated, the bombs
exploded at the height of the rush hour.

1112
01:30:56,500 --> 01:30:58,300
Why are you all against this?

1113
01:31:05,600 --> 01:31:07,900
Why are you so afraid of this?

1114
01:31:08,400 --> 01:31:09,800
This is real!

1115
01:31:10,000 --> 01:31:11,000
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1116
01:31:11,200 --> 01:31:13,000
This is scientific evidence...

1117
01:31:13,200 --> 01:31:16,200
...from well-known researchers
forced to work in secret.

1118
01:31:17,200 --> 01:31:21,300
A Nobel Prize winner, hounded
by the religious lobby. That's a story!

1119
01:31:22,400 --> 01:31:25,600
Better than a philandering,
dishonest old politician.

1120
01:31:25,800 --> 01:31:29,600
But a book like that would probably
have to be written in English...

1121
01:31:29,800 --> 01:31:31,500
...for the American market.

1122
01:31:32,600 --> 01:31:34,400
It happened to me, Michel.

1123
01:31:36,300 --> 01:31:38,200
I saw it with my own eyes.

1124
01:31:39,500 --> 01:31:41,000
Where we're going.

1125
01:31:43,000 --> 01:31:44,700
What we'll experience.

1126
01:31:46,400 --> 01:31:48,500
Each and every one of us.

1127
01:31:50,700 --> 01:31:52,400
That doesn't interest you?

1128
01:31:56,600 --> 01:32:00,100
Now listen, we commissioned a book
about Francois Mitterrand.

1129
01:32:00,600 --> 01:32:03,200
Either we agree on this
and you start writing it...

1130
01:32:03,400 --> 01:32:06,200
...or else I want my money back.
That's all I can say.

1131
01:32:30,000 --> 01:32:31,600
It was so humiliating.

1132
01:32:33,200 --> 01:32:35,900
They looked at me as if I'd lost my mind.

1133
01:32:36,100 --> 01:32:38,800
Six months ago they begged me
to write about anything.

1134
01:32:39,700 --> 01:32:42,200
Anything by the great Marie Lelay.

1135
01:32:43,900 --> 01:32:47,600
You'd better give me my job back.
I've had enough with being humiliated.

1136
01:32:51,300 --> 01:32:53,300
Today, they even took down my posters.

1137
01:32:53,900 --> 01:32:55,200
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1138
01:32:56,800 --> 01:32:58,100
Why didn't you tell me?

1139
01:33:00,400 --> 01:33:01,600
And your book?

1140
01:33:03,600 --> 01:33:07,200
I'll finish it in my spare time.
It's caused me enough trouble as it is.

1141
01:33:10,600 --> 01:33:11,700
What's the matter?

1142
01:33:12,900 --> 01:33:14,100
Look...

1143
01:33:14,800 --> 01:33:17,100
...getting your job back...

1144
01:33:17,200 --> 01:33:19,400
...might not be as easy as you think.

1145
01:33:20,400 --> 01:33:21,400
Why?

1146
01:33:22,100 --> 01:33:24,400
It was a temporary break.
And on your advice.

1147
01:33:25,200 --> 01:33:26,300
I know, but...

1148
01:33:27,300 --> 01:33:29,000
What we couldn't have foreseen is...

1149
01:33:29,100 --> 01:33:32,100
...you'd be talking in public
about these experiences.

1150
01:33:32,300 --> 01:33:36,500
- That you'd lose your credibility.
- But I didn't want to write this book!

1151
01:33:36,700 --> 01:33:38,300
It was your idea!

1152
01:33:38,400 --> 01:33:40,900
It was my idea you should write
about Mitterrand.

1153
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:43,800
So, what are you saying?

1154
01:33:45,100 --> 01:33:47,600
I'm saying take some more time.

1155
01:33:47,800 --> 01:33:50,800
Finish the book, get it out
of your system, then come back.

1156
01:33:51,800 --> 01:33:54,100
It's that girl, isn't it?
My replacement?

1157
01:33:55,800 --> 01:33:57,800
I've watched her a few times.
She's good.

1158
01:33:58,200 --> 01:34:00,800
Yes, she is.
But not as good as you.

1159
01:34:02,500 --> 01:34:04,000
You're sleeping with her?

1160
01:34:05,400 --> 01:34:07,200
How can you say such a thing?

1161
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:12,500
You always told me to ask
the tough questions.

1162
01:34:26,500 --> 01:34:27,800
[SIGHS]

1163
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:31,400
It's funny...

1164
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:34,600
Who'd have thought it?

1165
01:34:37,100 --> 01:34:39,000
A few months ago I was famous.

1166
01:34:39,800 --> 01:34:41,300
Rich.

1167
01:34:42,900 --> 01:34:44,300
A success story.

1168
01:34:46,700 --> 01:34:48,100
I was happy.

1169
01:34:49,800 --> 01:34:51,900
Fulfilled by my work.

1170
01:34:53,500 --> 01:34:55,000
By you.

1171
01:35:10,000 --> 01:35:13,500
All this happened because
you didn't buy your kids their gifts.

1172
01:35:13,700 --> 01:35:15,100
Because of what?

1173
01:35:15,300 --> 01:35:17,900
What are you talking about?
I don't understand.

1174
01:35:19,500 --> 01:35:21,200
Forget it. It doesn't matter.

1175
01:35:22,400 --> 01:35:23,700
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1176
01:35:36,200 --> 01:35:38,200
[PHONE RINGING]

1177
01:35:39,500 --> 01:35:41,500
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

1178
01:35:42,200 --> 01:35:43,700
[MICHEL SPEAKS IN FRENCH
OVER PHONE]

1179
01:35:46,500 --> 01:35:47,500
MICHEL [OVER PHONE]:
It's Michel.

1180
01:35:49,200 --> 01:35:50,400
Listen...

1181
01:35:51,900 --> 01:35:54,600
I feel terrible about our meeting
earlier today.

1182
01:35:56,300 --> 01:35:58,900
This book is obviously
very important to you.

1183
01:36:00,600 --> 01:36:04,100
I think everyone was a bit on edge
because of the events in London.

1184
01:36:06,400 --> 01:36:11,200
But I made a few calls. There are
two publishers who might be interested.

1185
01:36:11,900 --> 01:36:13,800
One American, one English.

1186
01:36:14,900 --> 01:36:16,000
Do you have a pen?

1187
01:36:16,200 --> 01:36:18,200
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

1188
01:36:23,800 --> 01:36:25,300
I'm listening.

1189
01:36:29,600 --> 01:36:30,900
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1190
01:36:41,900 --> 01:36:43,900
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

1191
01:36:47,200 --> 01:36:50,500
BILLY: Anyways, I thought this would be
a good group reading room.

1192
01:36:50,600 --> 01:36:51,700
Group reading?

1193
01:36:51,800 --> 01:36:54,300
Yeah, where you could
read more people at once.

1194
01:36:54,500 --> 01:36:57,800
Up to 20 people or more, it's up to you.
They'd pay lower rates that way.

1195
01:36:58,000 --> 01:37:00,100
This would be your personal
consulting room.

1196
01:37:00,200 --> 01:37:04,500
And right next door, George,
this is gonna be my room.

1197
01:37:04,700 --> 01:37:07,100
I'm gonna make sure
everything gets taken care of.

1198
01:37:07,300 --> 01:37:08,800
You won't have to worry.

1199
01:37:09,300 --> 01:37:11,800
I don't understand.
What about your other businesses?

1200
01:37:12,000 --> 01:37:13,700
Oh, yeah, of course. They're gone.

1201
01:37:13,900 --> 01:37:16,000
Once this thing takes off,
forget it, you know?

1202
01:37:16,200 --> 01:37:19,000
Let's get you home. You need rest.
You got a big day tomorrow.

1203
01:37:19,200 --> 01:37:21,100
You already have three appointments.

1204
01:37:21,300 --> 01:37:22,600
- All right?
- Yeah.

1205
01:37:22,800 --> 01:37:24,100
BILLY:
Come on.

1206
01:37:44,300 --> 01:37:45,500
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1207
01:37:50,500 --> 01:37:52,900
- You Billy Lonegan?
- Yes.

1208
01:37:53,000 --> 01:37:55,200
Before he went, your brother
asked me to give this to you.

1209
01:37:55,300 --> 01:37:56,800
Went? Went where?

1210
01:37:57,000 --> 01:37:58,500
I have no idea.

1211
01:38:05,000 --> 01:38:06,200
GEORGE:
Dear Billy...

1212
01:38:06,700 --> 01:38:08,000
...I'm sorry.

1213
01:38:08,200 --> 01:38:11,300
I guess there's nothing I'll ever
be able to say to persuade you...

1214
01:38:11,500 --> 01:38:14,000
...that what I have isn't a gift,
but a curse.

1215
01:38:14,700 --> 01:38:17,900
I know you feel what I have
comes with a duty to help others.

1216
01:38:18,100 --> 01:38:21,500
But right now, the person
I most need to help is myself.

1217
01:38:21,700 --> 01:38:24,100
So I've decided to take some time out.

1218
01:38:24,300 --> 01:38:27,200
I don't know what the future will bring
or when I'll be back.

1219
01:38:27,400 --> 01:38:29,900
So don't wait up, so to speak.

1220
01:38:30,000 --> 01:38:33,900
Love to Jenni and the kids.
Your baby brother, George.

1221
01:38:48,400 --> 01:38:51,400
You know the recovery rate
in substance abuse cases like this.

1222
01:38:51,900 --> 01:38:54,100
- Yeah.
- Yeah. Very low.

1223
01:38:55,100 --> 01:38:58,400
So, what's the best way forward?
Are you okay for a little bit longer?

1224
01:39:00,000 --> 01:39:03,500
Yes. But not too long, please.

1225
01:39:03,700 --> 01:39:07,100
We're running out of ideas,
and it's beginning to take its toll.

1226
01:39:07,600 --> 01:39:10,000
Taking him to see
our previous child, Ricky.

1227
01:39:12,000 --> 01:39:14,800
Who knows, you know?
One kid talking to another.

1228
01:39:27,500 --> 01:39:29,300
MAN: Marie Lelay?
MARIE [IN ENGLISH]: Yes?

1229
01:39:29,400 --> 01:39:33,600
MAN: This is Richard Aronson
of Aquarius Books in Santa Fe, New Mexico.

1230
01:39:33,800 --> 01:39:35,100
MARIE:
Excuse me?

1231
01:39:35,300 --> 01:39:39,000
MAN: Aquarius books in Santa Fe?
A few months ago, you sent us your book.

1232
01:39:39,100 --> 01:39:41,200
I'm just ringing to say
how much we liked it.

1233
01:39:41,400 --> 01:39:44,700
Sorry it's taken so long, but we loved it,
and we'd like to publish it.

1234
01:39:44,900 --> 01:39:47,000
MARIE: Really?
MAN: In fact, we'd like to print it...

1235
01:39:47,200 --> 01:39:50,200
...in time for a book fair in London
in the spring.

1236
01:39:50,400 --> 01:39:52,500
- You're based in Paris?
MARIE: Yes.

1237
01:39:52,700 --> 01:39:56,000
MAN: So, if we were to ask,
going to London wouldn't be inconvenient?

1238
01:39:56,200 --> 01:39:58,100
MARIE:
No. No, no, no, not at all.

1239
01:39:58,300 --> 01:40:00,800
MAN: That would be a good opportunity
to do some publicity.

1240
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:03,900
Maybe a reading. It's an incredible story.

1241
01:40:04,100 --> 01:40:05,900
MARIE:
Thank you.

1242
01:40:11,700 --> 01:40:13,400
TOUR GUIDE:
And here we are.

1243
01:40:15,400 --> 01:40:17,900
48 Doughty Street.

1244
01:40:18,100 --> 01:40:19,800
Charles Dickens' home in London...

1245
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:23,800
...where he lived with his wife Catherine
and their children.

1246
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:26,600
Anyone know how many children?

1247
01:40:26,800 --> 01:40:28,200
[TOURISTS MURMURING INDISTINCTLY]

1248
01:40:28,400 --> 01:40:30,500
Here we are in the main hallway.

1249
01:40:30,700 --> 01:40:33,200
- This is the view that greeted the author...
- Ten.

1250
01:40:33,300 --> 01:40:35,000
...as he walked in each time.

1251
01:40:35,200 --> 01:40:38,000
Everything has been preserved
exactly as it was.

1252
01:40:38,200 --> 01:40:42,400
So just follow me up the stairs.
We'll start at the top of the house.

1253
01:40:45,700 --> 01:40:48,200
Now we move in to Dickens' study.

1254
01:40:48,400 --> 01:40:52,300
And directly in front of you, you'll see
an original copy of A Christmas Carol...

1255
01:40:52,500 --> 01:40:55,700
...arguably one of Dickens'
most famous books.

1256
01:40:56,200 --> 01:40:59,300
But over here, the thing I expect
most of you have come to see.

1257
01:40:59,500 --> 01:41:01,700
Dickens' desk,
where he wrote most of his books.

1258
01:41:02,500 --> 01:41:07,100
On this wall we have several illustrations
for The Mystery of Edwin Drood...

1259
01:41:07,200 --> 01:41:10,300
...the novel Dickens was writing
at the time of his death.

1260
01:41:11,100 --> 01:41:14,900
And on the far wall here,
a painting loved by Dickens fans.

1261
01:41:15,100 --> 01:41:17,600
It shows the author asleep at his desk...

1262
01:41:17,700 --> 01:41:20,800
...with characters from his novels
floating in the air around him.

1263
01:41:22,200 --> 01:41:24,500
Anyone know its name?

1264
01:41:24,600 --> 01:41:26,300
Dickens' Dream.

1265
01:41:26,500 --> 01:41:29,700
TOUR GUIDE:
It's called Dickens' Dream.

1266
01:41:33,000 --> 01:41:34,300
This way, please.

1267
01:41:36,600 --> 01:41:40,000
Just gather again at the front
of the building.

1268
01:41:46,200 --> 01:41:48,200
Does anyone have any questions?

1269
01:41:53,700 --> 01:41:55,500
GEORGE:
What is the date today?

1270
01:41:55,700 --> 01:41:59,000
TOUR GUIDE: Fourteenth.
- It is the 14th. Yeah, okay.

1271
01:42:02,400 --> 01:42:04,400
I think you'll like Ricky.

1272
01:42:04,600 --> 01:42:08,300
He was about your age when he first
came to us, and just as shy.

1273
01:42:08,900 --> 01:42:13,200
Now he's a grown man.
With a job and his own flat.

1274
01:42:17,600 --> 01:42:20,300
DENNIS: He's in here somewhere.
ANGELA: He said he'd meet us at the front.

1275
01:42:20,500 --> 01:42:22,300
DENNIS:
Where is he?

1276
01:42:22,500 --> 01:42:25,300
ANGELA: Where is he?
DENNIS: Hey. Look at this.

1277
01:42:25,500 --> 01:42:27,200
- Hey.
RICKY: Heh, heh, heh.

1278
01:42:30,200 --> 01:42:32,600
Oh, my God, I hardly recognized you.

1279
01:42:32,800 --> 01:42:35,600
- You gonna arrest us?
- Yeah. Not if you behave yourself.

1280
01:42:35,800 --> 01:42:37,800
Marcus, this is Ricky.

1281
01:42:38,000 --> 01:42:39,700
RICKY:
You all right, mate?

1282
01:42:39,900 --> 01:42:41,100
Fancy a coffee first?

1283
01:42:41,300 --> 01:42:43,400
- Yeah, that's a great idea.
- Yeah, great idea.

1284
01:42:44,400 --> 01:42:46,300
It's an amazing place, isn't it?

1285
01:42:46,500 --> 01:42:47,800
Can I have a look around?

1286
01:42:49,500 --> 01:42:52,300
Yeah. But meet us back here
in one hour, yeah?

1287
01:42:52,800 --> 01:42:54,600
- Good lad.
- Okay?

1288
01:42:57,900 --> 01:43:01,300
It's been nearly a year.
He hardly speaks to us.

1289
01:43:01,500 --> 01:43:03,100
Neither did I, remember?

1290
01:43:03,300 --> 01:43:06,100
This one's different. He's not like you.

1291
01:43:07,100 --> 01:43:09,000
RICKY: Let's have that coffee, yeah?
- Yeah.

1292
01:43:09,200 --> 01:43:10,900
RICKY:
Oh, lovely.

1293
01:43:11,800 --> 01:43:13,800
[CHATTERING]

1294
01:43:24,600 --> 01:43:29,500
MAN [OVER MICROPHONE]: "'She is,
I do assure you, the winegariest person.'

1295
01:43:30,300 --> 01:43:34,800
Mr. Plornish, with a modest
disavowal of his merits...

1296
01:43:35,000 --> 01:43:37,700
...opened the room door
for her readmission...

1297
01:43:37,900 --> 01:43:41,300
...and followed her in with such
an exceedingly bald presence...

1298
01:43:41,500 --> 01:43:43,500
...of not having been out at all...

1299
01:43:43,700 --> 01:43:47,600
...that her father might have observed it
without being very suspicious.

1300
01:43:47,800 --> 01:43:52,200
In his affable unconsciousness,
however, he took no heed.

1301
01:43:52,400 --> 01:43:56,500
Plornish, after the little conversation,
took his leave.

1302
01:43:56,700 --> 01:43:59,000
Making the tour of the prison
before he left...

1303
01:43:59,200 --> 01:44:02,000
...and looking on at a game of skittles...

1304
01:44:02,200 --> 01:44:04,600
...with the mixed feelings
of an old inhabitant...

1305
01:44:04,700 --> 01:44:07,900
...who had his private reasons
for believing...

1306
01:44:08,100 --> 01:44:13,400
...that it might be his destiny
to come back again."

1307
01:44:16,800 --> 01:44:18,400
Thank you.

1308
01:44:19,900 --> 01:44:21,200
Thank you.

1309
01:44:21,400 --> 01:44:26,100
Now, if any of you wish to purchase a CD,
I am at your disposal.

1310
01:44:26,200 --> 01:44:28,200
- Thank you.
JACOBI: Thank you.

1311
01:44:28,400 --> 01:44:30,100
- Hello.
- Hi. George.

1312
01:44:30,200 --> 01:44:31,800
- To George.
- Yeah. George Lonegan.

1313
01:44:32,000 --> 01:44:33,200
To George.

1314
01:44:33,300 --> 01:44:36,600
I'm a... It's... This
is an honor, Mr. Jacobi.

1315
01:44:36,800 --> 01:44:39,400
I'm a really big fan. You have no idea.

1316
01:44:39,600 --> 01:44:41,600
Thank you.
You're a long way from home.

1317
01:44:41,800 --> 01:44:43,600
- Yes.
- Yes.

1318
01:44:44,700 --> 01:44:47,500
- Did you enjoy it?
- Very much, yes.

1319
01:44:50,000 --> 01:44:52,600
- There you are. Thank you.
- Thank you so much. Thank you.

1320
01:44:52,900 --> 01:44:54,800
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

1321
01:44:57,700 --> 01:45:00,100
MARIE [OVER MICROPHONE]:
"I felt connected to another world...

1322
01:45:00,300 --> 01:45:04,000
...a place of utter peace and tranquility.

1323
01:45:05,600 --> 01:45:09,700
Whether what I saw was a genuine
glimpse of the afterlife...

1324
01:45:09,900 --> 01:45:13,300
...or just a concussed fantasy,
I'll probably never know.

1325
01:45:14,100 --> 01:45:19,000
I arrive at the end of my journey
with as many question as I started with.

1326
01:45:23,600 --> 01:45:26,700
I certainly never imagined
I would be exposed...

1327
01:45:26,900 --> 01:45:30,300
...to that kind of prejudice
and close-mindedness.

1328
01:45:30,500 --> 01:45:33,500
We obviously still have
a long way to go...

1329
01:45:33,600 --> 01:45:37,800
...before we will be able to deal
with death and what follows...

1330
01:45:37,900 --> 01:45:41,000
...in anything approaching
a sensible fashion."

1331
01:45:44,300 --> 01:45:49,000
Okay, so if you want to buy my book,
I can sign it.

1332
01:45:49,200 --> 01:45:50,900
You're welcome. Thank you.

1333
01:45:51,100 --> 01:45:53,100
[CROWD CLAPPING]

1334
01:45:58,700 --> 01:46:00,200
- Hello. What's your name?
MARIA: Hello.

1335
01:46:00,400 --> 01:46:02,300
- Maria.
- Maria.

1336
01:46:08,300 --> 01:46:10,700
- Thank you, Maria.
- Thank you very much.

1337
01:46:10,800 --> 01:46:13,300
MICHAEL: Michael.
- Michael. Okay.

1338
01:46:19,900 --> 01:46:21,300
Thank you.

1339
01:46:21,500 --> 01:46:23,500
Honora.

1340
01:46:27,600 --> 01:46:29,100
MARIE: Thank you.
- Thank you.

1341
01:46:29,300 --> 01:46:32,000
- My name's George.
- George.

1342
01:46:42,800 --> 01:46:44,100
[WHOOSH]

1343
01:46:52,800 --> 01:46:54,200
WOMAN: To Penny.
- Sorry?

1344
01:46:54,400 --> 01:46:55,800
- Penny.
- Penny.

1345
01:47:01,800 --> 01:47:05,300
MARCUS:
Wait a minute. I recognize you.

1346
01:47:05,500 --> 01:47:06,700
Sorry?

1347
01:47:06,900 --> 01:47:08,500
You're that psychic.

1348
01:47:10,300 --> 01:47:13,400
No, no. Um... No, you got me mistaken
with someone else.

1349
01:47:13,600 --> 01:47:15,600
Yes, you are. You're George Lonegan.

1350
01:47:15,700 --> 01:47:19,600
- I don't even know who that is. No, I'm not.
- You are George Lonegan.

1351
01:47:20,300 --> 01:47:22,000
- You got me...
- I need to talk to you.

1352
01:47:22,200 --> 01:47:24,900
No, you got me mixed up
with someone else.

1353
01:47:25,100 --> 01:47:27,400
Please, I need to talk to you.
You're a psychic.

1354
01:47:27,600 --> 01:47:29,300
I'm not. I'm not who you think I am.

1355
01:47:29,500 --> 01:47:32,900
I saw it on the Internet.
You are a psychic.

1356
01:47:33,600 --> 01:47:35,900
What? What is it? What do you want?

1357
01:47:36,100 --> 01:47:39,200
If it's a reading, I have news for you.
I don't do it anymore.

1358
01:47:39,400 --> 01:47:41,400
Now leave me alone.

1359
01:47:45,500 --> 01:47:48,400
MAN [OVER MICROPHONE]:
"When I look back on this, it was insane.

1360
01:47:48,500 --> 01:47:51,800
The rudder cables became useless
and I lost my ability to steer.

1361
01:47:52,000 --> 01:47:55,600
I was helpless amid the swirling
maritime mass of industry.

1362
01:47:55,800 --> 01:47:58,400
The sea had turned malevolently dark.

1363
01:47:58,600 --> 01:48:02,900
What had once seemed friendly was now
a violent monster trying to kill me."

1364
01:48:03,600 --> 01:48:06,800
Did you see a Frenchwoman who was
here just a few minutes ago?

1365
01:48:06,900 --> 01:48:09,300
She's gone. She left already.

1366
01:48:10,900 --> 01:48:12,400
MAN:
"You realize you're in danger...

1367
01:48:12,600 --> 01:48:15,800
...and dwell on how things might end.
I spent every second..."

1368
01:49:14,100 --> 01:49:16,300
CLERK: Hi, can I help you?
- I'm looking for someone.

1369
01:49:16,500 --> 01:49:18,200
CLERK:
Come on, please. Move along.

1370
01:49:36,300 --> 01:49:38,300
[CROWD CHEERING ON TV]

1371
01:49:41,400 --> 01:49:43,900
MAN [ON TV]: Hill cuts it back nicely,
perhaps almost too far.

1372
01:49:44,200 --> 01:49:47,200
But it's gone in! It's gone in!

1373
01:49:47,400 --> 01:49:49,700
Andy Fisher!

1374
01:49:49,900 --> 01:49:52,500
You have to question that play...

1375
01:50:06,000 --> 01:50:07,500
GEORGE:
Okay.

1376
01:50:09,000 --> 01:50:10,900
We better get you inside.

1377
01:50:14,000 --> 01:50:15,700
Come on.

1378
01:50:19,300 --> 01:50:21,600
- What's your name?
- Marcus.

1379
01:50:32,600 --> 01:50:37,500
Okay. Couple of ground rules
before we get started.

1380
01:50:38,300 --> 01:50:39,700
I'm sorry about the woman.

1381
01:50:39,800 --> 01:50:41,000
What woman?

1382
01:50:41,100 --> 01:50:43,100
The woman at the book fair.

1383
01:50:44,200 --> 01:50:46,300
I could tell you liked her.

1384
01:50:46,700 --> 01:50:47,800
No, I didn't.

1385
01:50:48,000 --> 01:50:50,900
Yes, you did.
So I'm sorry for taking you away.

1386
01:50:51,100 --> 01:50:55,500
I don't have any idea what you're
talking about. Here, sit down.

1387
01:50:57,200 --> 01:50:58,700
Okay.

1388
01:50:59,700 --> 01:51:01,100
Let's do this.

1389
01:51:02,100 --> 01:51:04,900
Okay, I'm gonna grab your hands
because it seems to help...

1390
01:51:05,100 --> 01:51:06,700
...and then I'll let go.

1391
01:51:08,100 --> 01:51:11,600
Don't worry, I'm not gonna go into
any stupid trance or anything like that.

1392
01:51:11,800 --> 01:51:15,500
I just gotta grab them to get a connection,
then I'll let go. Okay?

1393
01:51:15,600 --> 01:51:19,100
Now, I want you to answer yes or no
to everything I ask.

1394
01:51:19,300 --> 01:51:21,500
- You understand?
- Yes.

1395
01:51:21,700 --> 01:51:23,200
Okay.

1396
01:51:24,300 --> 01:51:26,100
Let's see them.

1397
01:51:32,000 --> 01:51:33,000
[WHOOSH]

1398
01:51:39,500 --> 01:51:40,600
Okay.

1399
01:51:43,200 --> 01:51:45,700
Okay, someone close to you
has passed away?

1400
01:51:46,300 --> 01:51:47,700
Yes.

1401
01:51:48,500 --> 01:51:49,500
A male?

1402
01:51:51,200 --> 01:51:52,700
Yes.

1403
01:51:53,200 --> 01:51:55,600
He was young when he died.

1404
01:51:55,800 --> 01:51:57,300
Yes.

1405
01:51:58,200 --> 01:52:00,300
This person your brother?

1406
01:52:04,900 --> 01:52:06,700
Older brother.

1407
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:12,300
But not by much, he says.

1408
01:52:14,100 --> 01:52:16,200
Only by a few minutes.

1409
01:52:18,900 --> 01:52:20,700
I'm sorry, kid.

1410
01:52:23,900 --> 01:52:28,500
I gotta concentrate.
This guy... This guy talks a lot.

1411
01:52:28,600 --> 01:52:30,600
Talks fast.

1412
01:52:30,700 --> 01:52:33,000
Got a really weird laugh.

1413
01:52:33,900 --> 01:52:36,600
Okay. Ahem. He says...

1414
01:52:37,300 --> 01:52:40,000
...there's so much he wants to tell you.

1415
01:52:41,400 --> 01:52:43,400
You wouldn't believe how it is.

1416
01:52:43,900 --> 01:52:46,400
How you can be all things...

1417
01:52:47,700 --> 01:52:49,500
...and all at once.

1418
01:52:51,500 --> 01:52:53,200
And the weightlessness.

1419
01:52:53,700 --> 01:52:55,800
He says that's cool.

1420
01:52:56,800 --> 01:52:58,300
Now he's laughing.

1421
01:53:00,200 --> 01:53:01,900
He's got a funny laugh.

1422
01:53:02,200 --> 01:53:03,700
Um...

1423
01:53:04,600 --> 01:53:06,000
Okay.

1424
01:53:09,300 --> 01:53:12,500
He says how you
always looked up to him...

1425
01:53:13,200 --> 01:53:17,000
...and relied on him
to make the decision...

1426
01:53:17,700 --> 01:53:20,400
...how maybe you used that
as an excuse.

1427
01:53:21,600 --> 01:53:23,200
Is that true?

1428
01:53:24,200 --> 01:53:27,000
Okay. He says can't do that anymore.

1429
01:53:29,600 --> 01:53:31,200
Now you're on your own.

1430
01:53:33,100 --> 01:53:36,800
Okay, now, hang on, okay, now.
Now he's saying something about a hat.

1431
01:53:37,700 --> 01:53:39,300
The cap?

1432
01:53:39,500 --> 01:53:41,800
A cap. Okay.

1433
01:53:44,900 --> 01:53:48,800
He says to take it off right now.
Take it off.

1434
01:53:51,000 --> 01:53:53,800
He doesn't...
He's telling you not to wear it again...

1435
01:53:55,300 --> 01:53:57,300
...because it was his.

1436
01:53:58,600 --> 01:54:01,900
And that's why he knocked it off
your head that day?

1437
01:54:03,600 --> 01:54:06,700
At the tube? Do you know
what he's talking about?

1438
01:54:08,700 --> 01:54:10,100
Okay.

1439
01:54:11,000 --> 01:54:14,700
He says good thing he did too.

1440
01:54:20,800 --> 01:54:23,900
And that's the last time
he's ever looking out for you.

1441
01:54:25,800 --> 01:54:27,200
I'm sorry. I'm, uh...

1442
01:54:31,300 --> 01:54:35,600
I'm sorry, I'm losing him now.
He's leaving. He wants to leave.

1443
01:54:40,300 --> 01:54:41,800
No, Jase.

1444
01:54:42,900 --> 01:54:44,100
Don't go.

1445
01:54:45,000 --> 01:54:47,900
You can't. Don't leave me.

1446
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:50,100
I don't wanna be here without you.

1447
01:54:51,200 --> 01:54:54,000
Please, Jase, don't go. I miss you.

1448
01:54:54,200 --> 01:54:57,900
Okay, he came back. He's here. He says...

1449
01:55:00,100 --> 01:55:04,400
...if you're worried about being
on your own, don't be.

1450
01:55:05,200 --> 01:55:06,400
You're not.

1451
01:55:06,700 --> 01:55:10,800
Because he is you and you are him.

1452
01:55:11,800 --> 01:55:13,400
One cell.

1453
01:55:13,700 --> 01:55:15,100
One person.

1454
01:55:16,700 --> 01:55:18,200
Always.

1455
01:55:19,200 --> 01:55:20,400
I miss you.

1456
01:55:21,300 --> 01:55:25,300
Please, Jase, don't go.
Please come back.

1457
01:55:25,500 --> 01:55:27,100
I miss you so badly.

1458
01:55:30,100 --> 01:55:34,000
Okay, wait. He's leaving again.
Hold on, hold on. I'm sorry.

1459
01:55:34,100 --> 01:55:35,400
Well, where's he gone?

1460
01:55:37,800 --> 01:55:40,200
I'm sorry, kid. I don't know.

1461
01:55:41,200 --> 01:55:43,400
But you've done all those readings.

1462
01:55:45,200 --> 01:55:47,000
I still don't know.

1463
01:55:48,500 --> 01:55:50,100
Sorry.

1464
01:55:58,700 --> 01:56:01,300
Okay. We better get you home.

1465
01:56:45,800 --> 01:56:47,800
[RINGING]

1466
01:56:50,900 --> 01:56:53,500
- Hello?
MARCUS [OVER PHONE]: May Fair.

1467
01:56:54,400 --> 01:56:55,400
What?

1468
01:56:55,800 --> 01:56:59,900
The hotel where she's staying.
The woman you like?

1469
01:57:01,300 --> 01:57:03,000
What are you talking about?

1470
01:57:03,200 --> 01:57:06,600
Well, I rang up the publisher
and said I heard her speak...

1471
01:57:06,800 --> 01:57:10,200
...wanted to drop off a letter
saying how interesting it was.

1472
01:57:10,300 --> 01:57:12,000
Anyway, that's the name.

1473
01:57:12,200 --> 01:57:13,400
May Fair.

1474
01:57:13,500 --> 01:57:17,300
Okay, well, that's really interesting,
but what does that have to do with me?

